// 46-fn-arenas — m49: free-fn implicit-locus arenas.
//
// Pre-m49 every free-fn allocation lived in the program-wide
// arena.global and was reclaimed only at process exit. A loop
// that called a String-returning helper N times kept N copies
// of the rendered string alive forever — fine for a short
// `lotus build && ./main`, ruinous for any long-running
// program.
//
// m49 makes every non-main free fn open a per-call subregion
// of the caller's arena at body entry. Body allocations route
// through that subregion. Heap-typed return values are deep-
// copied into the caller's arena before the subregion is
// destroyed, so they outlive the call. Stack-flat values
// (Int / Float / Bool / Decimal-i128 / Time / Duration /
// no-payload-Enum) skip the copy — they're already in
// registers across the call boundary.
//
// This example exercises the code path: a `decorate` helper
// that builds a fresh String per call (concat-driven, so the
// body genuinely allocates inside the subregion) gets called
// in a loop. After m49 the subregion is wholesale-freed at
// each return; only the deep-copied final String survives in
// main's arena. Pre-m49 every intermediate concat product
// would have been retained until process exit.
//
// Functional output is the same on both backends — the win is
// invisible at the print layer (it's a memory-shape change).
// What this example tests is that the deep-copy path is
// correct: if the subregion-destroy ran *before* the copy, or
// if the copy missed a tuple field, the final printed value
// would be garbage on the codegen path. Parity with the
// interpreter (which uses Rust ownership and is unaffected by
// m49) catches that class of bug immediately.

fn decorate(name: String, n: Int) -> String {
    // Two concat allocations land in the per-call subregion.
    // Only the final result needs to survive past the return —
    // m49's deep-copy handles that, the rest get wholesale-
    // freed when the subregion is destroyed.
    return "[" + name + ":" + to_string(n) + "]";
}

fn pair(a: Int, b: Int) -> (Int, String) {
    // Tuple return: storage struct allocated in the subregion
    // first, then deep-copied into the caller's arena field-
    // by-field. The String field itself recurses through
    // emit_return_value_deep_copy so its buffer also lands in
    // the caller's arena.
    return (a + b, decorate("sum", a + b));
}

fn main() {
    // Loop the helper enough times that pre-m49 you'd notice
    // the leak under valgrind. Functional output stays small
    // so the example reads cleanly.
    for i in 1..=5 {
        let s: String = decorate("tick", i);
        println(s);
    }

    // Tuple with a String inside — recursive deep-copy.
    let (sum, label) = pair(10, 32);
    println("sum = ", sum);
    println("label = ", label);
}
